Executive Summary:
Approach A is the right call. The estimator should remain a self-contained feature mounted under its own route shell, while showQuote stays local to the estimator module and continues controlling Estimator ↔ Quote transitions exactly as it does now. That preserves the current architecture in App.tsx while avoiding a full router rewrite, which the estimator guidelines explicitly warn against.

Approach A — Implementation Plan:

 • Top-level route shell only
Create a thin app boundary with four top-level routes: /, /auth, /portal, and /estimator. The estimator route should mount an EstimatorAppShell and keep the current estimator/quote state machine internal. Do not move Quote into its own route in Phase 1. The current app already uses a local showQuote boolean and conditional rendering for Estimator vs. Quote, so that logic should remain untouched inside the estimator feature.

 • Refactor App.tsx into shells, not a rewrite

Split responsibilities into:
 • MarketingAppShell
 • AuthGatewayPage
 • PortalAppShell
 • EstimatorAppShell

Move the current estimator logic from src/App.tsx into EstimatorAppShell.tsx with no behavioral changes. That shell should still own showQuote, quoteData, formData, currentStep, aiActionTrigger, and aiUsageCount. This is the key technical-debt control point.
 • Portal auth guard at route boundary only
Protect /portal with an auth/session guard. Do not make the estimator itself auth-blocked in the first pass unless you explicitly want lead capture before estimator access. This reduces blast radius and keeps current estimator conversion behavior stable.
 • Lifecycle-first portal data model
Before any Figma dashboard work, define canonical objects:
QuoteRecord, OpportunityRecord, ProjectRecord, ActivityEvent.
Use the lifecycle states we locked earlier:
draft, scoping, quoted, sent, revision_requested, accepted, declined, expired for quotes;
intake, discovery, scoping, design_in_progress, build_in_progress, awaiting_client, blocked, uat, completed, archived for projects.

The portal UI must render against these states, not ad hoc labels.
 • Backend-triggered case-study email only

Bind the main-site case-study CTA to a Supabase Edge Function under /make-server-07a007e1/request-case-study. The estimator guidelines require that backend route prefix, and the current main-site CTA is only a visual button, so this remains net-new backend orchestration rather than a front-end email feature.


